106  Lewis LD, Weiner VS, Mukamel EA, Donoghue JA, Eskandar EN, Madsen JR, Anderson WS, Hochberg LR, Cash SS, Brown EN et al.: Rapid fragmentation of neuronal networks at the onset of propofol-induced unconsciousness. 
Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A 2012, 109:E3377-E3386. 
In this rare study, single-neuron recordings were obtained while three epilepsy patients underwent propofol anesthesia. 
The loss of consciousness was associated with a sudden onset of slow oscillations (<1 Hz) in the local field potential. Local neuronal networks continued to exhibit spiking activity, but this activity became fragmented in time by the slow oscillations, and decorrelated in space as the oscillations were asynchronous across distant sites. 
The suggestion is that temporal and spatial disintegration of cortical activity may cause a loss of consciousness. 
